Identify all database transactions. Locate all SQL queries throughout your application. Example:
      "select user from myappUsers where user = ? and pass = ?;"



        Verify that each transaction uses Stored Procedures. Verify that your application interacts with the backend database through the use of Stored Procedures. Ensure that all SQL queries look like:
      Connection.prepareStatement("exec PlaceOrder(?, ?, ?);");
      and not like:
      Connection.prepareStatement("insert into PendingPurchases "               + "(customer, item, quantity) values (?, ?, ?);");
      Some databases (or versions) do not support stored procedures. If possible, use a database product that supports stored procedures. If that is not possible, then continue to use prepared statements in conjunction with strong input validation.



        Verify that each transaction uses Prepared Statement. Verify that each SQL query is executed through the use of a PreparedStatement object. Example:
      Connection cn = MyApp.getDBConnection();PreparedStatement st = cn.prepareStatement(   "select user from myappUsers where user = ? and pass = ?;");st.setString(1, user);st.setString(2, new String(passDigest));ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery();

